who end up swallowing the

00:54:19.452 --> 00:54:21.740
little fish instead, so they
have a bad reputation.

00:54:21.740 --> 00:54:24.720
So the way these fish pick and
choose one another, it's

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:26.890
really regulated by the
laws of the market.

00:54:26.890 --> 00:54:30.060
So let me wrap this up now and
tell you why is it that we see

00:54:30.060 --> 00:54:32.750
all these similarities between
humans and other species and

00:54:32.750 --> 00:54:33.960
these games that we play.

00:54:33.960 --> 00:54:35.490
There's two processes that
account for these

00:54:35.490 --> 00:54:36.380
similarities.

00:54:36.380 --> 00:54:39.090
One is called convergent
evolution, the idea that

00:54:39.090 --> 00:54:42.000
organisms dealing with similar
social problems come up with

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.410
similar solutions
independently.

00:54:44.410 --> 00:54:47.190
And I mentioned some of
these situations--

00:54:47.190 --> 00:54:49.630
elevator effects,
market dynamics,

00:54:49.630 --> 00:54:51.440
cooperation, nepotism.

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:54.630
The other phenomenon is called
phylogenetic inheritance, the

00:54:54.630 --> 00:54:57.350
idea that two species that are
closely related might be

00:54:57.350 --> 00:55:00.010
similar in their behavior
because they inherit these

00:55:00.010 --> 00:55:01.740
behaviors from a common
ancestor.

00:55:01.740 --> 00:55:03.640
So for example, chimpanzees and

00:55:03.640 --> 00:55:05.360
humans are closely related.

00:55:05.360 --> 00:55:07.980
We're very similar in some
behaviors because we inherited

00:55:07.980 --> 00:55:10.270
these behaviors from an ancestor
that we share with

00:55:10.270 --> 00:55:12.990
chimpanzees about 5 to
6 million years ago.

00:55:12.990 --> 00:55:16.000
It's difficult to demonstrate
the inheritance of

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:17.780
behavior like this.

00:55:17.780 --> 00:55:20.350
But they say a picture's worth a
thousand words, so here's my

00:55:20.350 --> 00:55:21.320
contribution.

00:55:21.320 --> 00:55:23.540
This shows that even the most
beautiful human smile has a

00:55:23.540 --> 00:55:24.960
long evolutionary history.

00:55:24.960 --> 00:55:27.520
That's a smile in a rhesus
monkey and a chimpanzee, and

00:55:27.520 --> 00:55:28.910
that happens to be my wife.

