00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:41.710
comes with responsibility.

00:57:41.710 --> 00:57:44.700
So the fact that you have the
potential to make decisions

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:48.500
means that you need to do it
nicely, in a way that takes

00:57:48.500 --> 00:57:51.820
into account the needs and the
rights of other people.

00:57:51.820 --> 00:57:55.330
So there is a sort of a gentle,
kinder aspect to

00:57:55.330 --> 00:57:58.260
dominance which is an
opportunity if you happen to--

00:57:58.260 --> 00:58:00.160
you also have an opportunity
to lead.

00:58:00.160 --> 00:58:01.980
And if you have the ability
and the resources to lead,

00:58:01.980 --> 00:58:04.620
then there's nothing wrong
with that, right?

00:58:04.620 --> 00:58:07.008
AUDIENCE: Are you kind of
saying that despite our

00:58:07.008 --> 00:58:11.150
highest ideals that we're kind
of programmed to fall into

00:58:11.150 --> 00:58:12.800
those patterns of--?

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:13.900
DARIO MAESTRIPIERI: Well,
ask yourself.

00:58:13.900 --> 00:58:17.740
Usually, say, if I ask you to
think about 100 different

00:58:17.740 --> 00:58:19.940
relationships that you have with
people you know, starting

00:58:19.940 --> 00:58:23.230
with your family members, your
friends, and ask you to think

00:58:23.230 --> 00:58:25.820
whether you think you're
dominant or subordinate in

00:58:25.820 --> 00:58:27.990
each one of these relationships,
my guess is

00:58:27.990 --> 00:58:29.830
that you can give me
a good answer in at

00:58:29.830 --> 00:58:31.720
least 95% of the cases.

00:58:31.720 --> 00:58:34.410
I think if you think about it,
in 95% of your relationship,

00:58:34.410 --> 00:58:36.440
you have a pretty good idea
whether you're the one who

00:58:36.440 --> 00:58:38.050
calls the shots or
not so much.

00:58:38.050 --> 00:58:40.290
There might be 5% where
things are unclear.

00:58:40.290 --> 00:58:42.330
So does that mean dominance
is universal?

00:58:42.330 --> 00:58:45.496
I think it's pretty
pervasive, yeah.

00:58:45.496 --> 00:58:46.746
Yeah?

00:58:54.230 --> 00:58:56.180
AUDIENCE: Can I just follow
on from that?

00:58:56.180 --> 00:59:00.180
It seems to me there's another
big factor beyond dominance

00:59:00.180 --> 00:59:03.700
and cooperation and negotiation
which also is

00:59:03.700 --> 00:59:06.030
quite low cost, which is just
agreeing that you'll have

00:59:06.030 --> 00:59:07.740
certain customs and patterns.

00:59:07.740 --> 00:59:09.530
That's how my relationship
works with my wife.

00:59:09.530 --> 00:59:12.720
There are lots of things that we
need to do which has a cost

00:59:12.720 --> 00:59:14.150
to each of us, whoever
does it.

00:59:14.150 --> 00:59:16.450
But we've just agreed that one
of us will do one, generally,

00:59:16.450 --> 00:59:18.230
and the other will
do the other.

00:59:18.230 --> 00:59:18.790
DARIO MAESTRIPIERI:
That's great.

00:59:18.790 --> 00:59:22.640
There is division of labor and
there is ways to cooperate in

00:59:22.640 --> 00:59:24.180
a way that is complementary.

00:59:24.180 --> 00:59:27.770
But still, in every long-term
cooperative relationship,

00:59:27.770 --> 00:59:30.540
there is always the potential
for disagreements.

00:59:30.540 --> 00:59:34.010
No matter how good, how strong
your relationship is, you end

00:59:34.010 --> 00:59:37.660
up disagreeing over a number of
small issues, big issues on

00:59:37.660 --> 00:59:39.300
a daily basis.

00:59:39.300 --> 00:59:42.110
And this is not just
in humans.

00:59:42.110 --> 00:59:44.700
It happens in many species
of primates.

00:59:44.700 --> 00:59:47.350
Aggression and fighting is most
common between closely

00:59:47.350 --> 00:59:48.610
related individuals--

00:59:48.610 --> 00:59:52.120
pairs of siblings, mothers and
daughters, males and females

00:59:52.120 --> 00:59:53.400
who associate frequently.

00:59:53.400 --> 00:59:55.870
They fight with each
other all the time.

00:59:55.870 --> 00:59:59.080
The most frequent crimes are
committed in pairs of people

00:59:59.080 --> 01:00:00.150
who know each other well.

01:00:00.150 --> 01:00:01.750
So it's not that you go out
and kill strangers.

01:00:01.750 --> 01:00:04.480
You go and kill your wife or
your child, stuff like that.

01:00:04.480 --> 01:00:06.590
So your relationship can
be-- the point I'm

01:00:06.590 --> 01:00:07.670
trying to make is--

01:00:07.670 --> 01:00:09.340
I'm not trying to sell
some pessimistic

01:00:09.340 --> 01:00:11.190
view of human nature.

01:00:11.190 --> 01:00:14.110
But it's that its intrinsic to
the notion that if you're in a

01:00:14.110 --> 01:00:16.900
long-term relationship with
somebody, there's many

01:00:16.900 --> 01:00:21.120
opportunities for disagreeing
about the way you do things.

01:00:21.120 --> 01:00:24.840
And fighting all the time, or
negotiating all the time,

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:27.490
every single time, it's
just not productive.

01:00:27.490 --> 01:00:28.620
It's not cost effective.

01:00:28.620 --> 01:00:29.770
It's stressful.

01:00:29.770 --> 01:00:31.330
It's expensive energetically.

01:00:31.330 --> 01:00:34.460
It might damage your
relationship.

01:00:34.460 --> 01:00:36.230
It's not nice to negotiate
all the time.

01:00:36.230 --> 01:00:39.480
Sometimes it's nice to make
a decision and go on.

01:00:39.480 --> 01:00:41.940
And move on.

01:00:41.940 --> 01:00:44.770
AUDIENCE: Actually, it's similar
to what you're saying.

01:00:44.770 --> 01:00:48.530
Just thinking about lots of
different relationships, it

01:00:48.530 --> 01:00:53.400
strikes me as the dominance
interplay actually varies

01:00:53.400 --> 01:00:55.260
depending on what the topic
happens to be that they're

01:00:55.260 --> 01:00:56.210
discussing.

01:00:56.210 --> 01:01:01.520
So it's not like husband/wife,
employer/employee, the

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:04.400
dominant person's always the
same person throughout.

01:01:04.400 --> 01:01:10.110
So I didn't see much
coming out--

01:01:10.110 --> 01:01:11.260
DARIO MAESTRIPIERI: Dominance
is more complex than,

01:01:11.260 --> 01:01:13.810
obviously, the way
I presented it.

01:01:13.810 --> 01:01:16.140
So dominance, first of all,
is a characteristic of a

01:01:16.140 --> 01:01:18.170
relationship, not a
characteristic of an

01:01:18.170 --> 01:01:19.050
individual.

01:01:19.050 --> 01:01:21.040
Which means that you can be
dominant in one relationship

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:21.995
but subordinate in another.

01:01:21.995 --> 01:01:24.670
It depends on the relationship,
not on you.

01:01:24.670 --> 01:01:27.480
But it's also that there are
individuals who tend to act

01:01:27.480 --> 01:01:30.150
dominant, and to be dominant
in many relationships, and

01:01:30.150 --> 01:01:31.760
others instead who are
dominant in very few

01:01:31.760 --> 01:01:32.980
relationships.

01:01:32.980 --> 01:01:36.890
In some cases, dominance is
independent of context, which

01:01:36.890 --> 01:01:39.030
means that if you're dominant
in a relationship,

01:01:39.030 --> 01:01:39.830
you call the shots.

01:01:39.830 --> 01:01:42.070
You make decisions in every
single context.

01:01:42.070 --> 01:01:46.080
In some cases, dominance is
context dependent, which means

01:01:46.080 --> 01:01:49.340
that you make decisions about
one domain and the other

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:50.990
person makes the decisions
in another domain.

01:01:50.990 --> 01:01:53.910
There's differences between
species and the extent to

01:01:53.910 --> 01:01:55.380
which this happens.

01:01:55.380 --> 01:01:58.670
In general, if there is a large
difference in dominance,

01:01:58.670 --> 01:02:01.230
so if you're really of a
higher status than your

01:02:01.230 --> 01:02:04.240
partner is, you tend
to make most

01:02:04.240 --> 01:02:06.390
decisions across contests.

01:02:06.390 --> 01:02:07.950
But it's sensitive to the
environment, to the

01:02:07.950 --> 01:02:09.160
characteristic of the
other individual.

01:02:09.160 --> 01:02:11.310
It's not a unitary concept.

01:02:11.310 --> 01:02:13.376
It can be complex to explain.

01:02:13.376 --> 01:02:15.110
FEMALE SPEAKER: Can we just
take two more questions?

01:02:15.110 --> 01:02:16.100
Is that OK?

01:02:16.100 --> 01:02:17.980
Because there's one
over there.

01:02:17.980 --> 01:02:21.400
AUDIENCE: My question is, one
thing you started out with in

01:02:21.400 --> 01:02:24.760
your lecture, or in your story
here, is basically that pretty

01:02:24.760 --> 01:02:28.390
much everything humans do has a
at least rudimentary version

01:02:28.390 --> 01:02:30.370
in the animal kingdom,
correct?

01:02:30.370 --> 01:02:33.120
DARIO MAESTRIPIERI: In some
primate species, yes.

01:02:33.120 --> 01:02:33.710
Not everything.

01:02:33.710 --> 01:02:35.280
Not everything.

01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:37.710
AUDIENCE: But then you go on
and you say, oh, but humans

01:02:37.710 --> 01:02:38.890
are special.

01:02:38.890 --> 01:02:39.860
And I don't get that.

01:02:39.860 --> 01:02:42.690
Why are you suddenly-- are you
saying humans have a soul,

01:02:42.690 --> 01:02:43.870
something that is not--

01:02:43.870 --> 01:02:46.550
DARIO MAESTRIPIERI: OK,
so humans are special.

01:02:46.550 --> 01:02:49.240
And every animal species
is special.

01:02:49.240 --> 01:02:50.590
Your domestic cat is special.

01:02:50.590 --> 01:02:51.280
They're not like dogs.

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:52.490
Dogs are special.

01:02:52.490 --> 01:02:54.330
Chimpanzees are special.

01:02:54.330 --> 01:02:56.510
Every species is special
in its own way.

01:02:56.510 --> 01:02:59.880
Humans are special when compared
to other primates,

01:02:59.880 --> 01:03:02.130
especially because we have
a very large brain.

01:03:02.130 --> 01:03:05.000
So our large brain essentially
allows us to do things with

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:07.500
our minds that other animals
don't do, which is, for

01:03:07.500 --> 01:03:10.380
example, produce abstract
thought.

01:03:10.380 --> 01:03:12.710
We are unique in the animal
world in our ability to think

01:03:12.710 --> 01:03:16.240
about things that don't exist in
reality, that exist only at

01:03:16.240 --> 01:03:17.580
an abstract level.

01:03:17.580 --> 01:03:20.310
Also, we're unique in our
ability to think about

01:03:20.310 --> 01:03:23.170
religion, to think about God,
to think about spirituality,

01:03:23.170 --> 01:03:26.810
to think about the future and
plan years in advance of

01:03:26.810 --> 01:03:31.690
things that might happen, to
produce art, for example.

01:03:31.690 --> 01:03:34.620
So there's all these ways-- and
to produce cultures and

01:03:34.620 --> 01:03:37.110
laws and moralities, and
things like that.

01:03:37.110 --> 01:03:39.700
I didn't say much about this
stuff because that's not what

01:03:39.700 --> 01:03:40.520
my book is about.

01:03:40.520 --> 01:03:42.660
My book is about social
relationships.

01:03:42.660 --> 01:03:46.180
So the idea here is that despite
of these large brains,

01:03:46.180 --> 01:03:49.580
and despite of this potential
that we have to think in

01:03:49.580 --> 01:03:53.140
abstract ways-- to be moral, to
be artistic, intellectual--

01:03:53.140 --> 01:03:55.260
when it comes to the day-to-day
problems of social

01:03:55.260 --> 01:03:58.460
relationships, we end up using
solutions that have been

01:03:58.460 --> 01:04:01.840
around a long time, that come
to us almost instinctively,

01:04:01.840 --> 01:04:05.010
that our mind unconsciously
processes.

01:04:05.010 --> 01:04:07.470
And so these solutions
are what we share

01:04:07.470 --> 01:04:08.570
with these other animals.

01:04:08.570 --> 01:04:12.230
So if I had written a book about
morality or God or art,

01:04:12.230 --> 01:04:16.790
obviously I would have less of
a reason about primates.

01:04:16.790 --> 01:04:19.190
But I do talk in one of
my chapters about--

01:04:19.190 --> 01:04:21.420
because actually, somebody
yesterday asked me this

01:04:21.420 --> 01:04:25.480
question, what about virtuous
people like artists or

01:04:25.480 --> 01:04:27.010
religious leaders.

01:04:27.010 --> 01:04:29.080
Can you compare those
to primates?

01:04:29.080 --> 01:04:31.060
They've accomplished so much.

01:04:31.060 --> 01:04:33.240
And the thing is that there's
always an interesting

01:04:33.240 --> 01:04:36.760
disconnect between what these
people have accomplished in

01:04:36.760 --> 01:04:40.150
their intellectual life, in
their public life, and what

01:04:40.150 --> 01:04:41.390
they do in their
personal lives.

01:04:41.390 --> 01:04:44.610
Sometimes talk about Pablo
Picasso and the issues he had

01:04:44.610 --> 01:04:45.800
in his private life.

01:04:45.800 --> 01:04:47.583
Sometimes you read about the
personal lives of these people

01:04:47.583 --> 01:04:50.110
who were very virtuous in
public, but they have a

01:04:50.110 --> 01:04:52.360
history of marriage and divorce,
of extramarital

01:04:52.360 --> 01:04:55.070
affairs, of greed for money,
and things like that.

01:04:55.070 --> 01:04:57.540
So when it comes to your
relationships and social

01:04:57.540 --> 01:05:00.640
lives, I think people are much
much more similar to each

01:05:00.640 --> 01:05:03.310
other than they are different
because we share this

01:05:03.310 --> 01:05:04.560
background.

01:05:07.750 --> 01:05:11.580
AUDIENCE: So when you gave a
comparison of communication

01:05:11.580 --> 01:05:16.495
with another person over email
or in life, then one thing

01:05:16.495 --> 01:05:19.830
came to my mind that with
internet and with email and

01:05:19.830 --> 01:05:22.750
instant messaging, you can
actually allow yourself to

01:05:22.750 --> 01:05:25.610
have conversations with several
different people.

01:05:25.610 --> 01:05:29.250
And these conversations will be
unrelated from each other.

01:05:29.250 --> 01:05:34.920
So does it somehow change
something in the patterns, or

01:05:34.920 --> 01:05:37.060
are there new patterns
appearing?

01:05:37.060 --> 01:05:38.490
DARIO MAESTRIPIERI: I'm
sure there are, yes.

01:05:38.490 --> 01:05:42.640
I'm sure there's all kinds of
new things that originate with

01:05:42.640 --> 01:05:45.370
the ability to interact
simultaneously

01:05:45.370 --> 01:05:47.740
with multiple people.

01:05:47.740 --> 01:05:50.630
But as there are benefits,
there's probably also costs.

01:05:50.630 --> 01:05:53.940
So there's something that you
lose if you don't have that

01:05:53.940 --> 01:05:55.780
direct, face-to-face
interactions.

01:05:55.780 --> 01:06:00.200
When we speak in person, we use
facial expressions, we use

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:04.130
hand gestures to tell the other
person, look, what I'm

01:06:04.130 --> 01:06:05.160
saying right now,
I mean it very

01:06:05.160 --> 01:06:07.410
seriously or just for fun.

01:06:07.410 --> 01:06:10.950
You can say, sometimes you
make me want to kill you.

01:06:10.950 --> 01:06:12.680
But if I say it with
a smile on my face,

01:06:12.680 --> 01:06:13.800
you know I'm joking.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:15.600
If I say it on email,
you don't know what

01:06:15.600 --> 01:06:16.070
to interpret that.

01:06:16.070 --> 01:06:17.990
You have to use a little
emoticon with a little smiley

01:06:17.990 --> 01:06:19.840
face to say I'm joking.

01:06:19.840 --> 01:06:22.520
But do emoticons really
do it all?

01:06:22.520 --> 01:06:28.590
Do they really replace all the
facial expressions, all the

01:06:28.590 --> 01:06:31.270
other gestures that we use to
supplement the information

01:06:31.270 --> 01:06:33.000
that we provide with
our words?

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:34.610
In my view, they don't.

01:06:34.610 --> 01:06:37.170
And also, there's all kinds of
other dynamics that come into

01:06:37.170 --> 01:06:40.990
play, including relative status,
costs and benefits,

01:06:40.990 --> 01:06:42.610
what your expect from
the relationship.

01:06:42.610 --> 01:06:46.200
That all plays a role in our
communication dynamics, no

01:06:46.200 --> 01:06:48.370
matter how high tech they are.

